expression.Value: The Calkin-Wilf correspondence

Cantor proved in 1874 that the set of the (positive) rational numbers is countable, this means that there is (at least one) way to define a biunivocal (one-to-one) correspondence between rational and natural numbers. Cantor provided one method.
Neil Calkin and Herbert Wilf published
with an alternative method to the one provided by Cantor. This method has several interesting properties.
In this document we show how Fōrmulæ can be used to make programs anc calculations about the Calkin-Wilf correspondence.

The Calkin-Wilf sequence

The Calkin-Wilf sequence is the list of rationals obtained from a breadth-first traversal of the Calkin–Wilf tree. Breadth-first traversal means "visit the nodes from levels, from the top and downwards, and in each level from left to right". If you do it for the first four levels you will get the sequence:

The correspondence

Once we have a way to convert the tree of unique rationals in a list (a sequence), it is easy to realize that there is a rule of correspondence between rationals and natural numbers: given a natural number n, its correspondent rational number is the elementof the sequence that appears at the position n, and viceversa, given a rational number r, its correspondent natural number is the position of the list where the number r appears.
From naturals to rationals
It is possible to calculate the rational from its position in a faster way.

Take the binary representation of the position. Startig from the root of the Calkin-Wilf tree, take the right node if the following binary digit is 1, and left otherwise (0). The node you stay after doing it with all the binary digits, contains the rational.
